%N A374805 a(n) is the smallest positive integer whose square can be represented as the sum of 3 distinct nonzero squares in exactly n ways, or -1 if no such number exists.
%C A374805 From _Zhao Hui Du_, Oct 10 2025 (Start)
%C A374805 Let 6r(m) be the number of integral solutions to x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = m^2,
%C A374805   2s(m) be the number of integral solutions to x^2 + 2y^2 = m^2,
%C A374805   4t(m) be the number of integral solutions to x^2 + y^2 = m^2.
%C A374805 Then the number of positive integral solutions with 0<x<y<z and x^2+y^2+z^2 = m^2 is f(m) = (6r(m)-12s(m)-12t(m)+18)/48.
%C A374805 Since f(2m)=f(m), a(n) must be an odd positive integer or -1.
%C A374805 The Olds paper gives formula of r(m) and for odd m, it is easy to prove r(m)>=m.
%C A374805 In BBS, we proved s(m) <= 2m^0.75 and t(m) <= 2m^0.75, so that we could give lower bound of f(m). (End)
